00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:27.030
So first of all,
what we are going

00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:31.990
to do for several lectures
is to talk about the layout

00:07:31.990 --> 00:07:35.620
and organization of the
visual system itself.

00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:42.520
Most of it we will discuss as
it applies to higher mammals,

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:47.280
in particular monkeys
and primates and humans.

00:07:49.210 --> 00:07:53.580
Then we are going to talk
about specific aspects

00:07:53.580 --> 00:07:55.390
of visual processing.

00:07:55.390 --> 00:08:00.220
We're going to try to understand
how we adapt in vision,

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:03.370
and, very interestingly,
how we are

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:06.995
able to perceive colors and
process them accurately.

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:11.180
Another fascinating
topic is how we

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:15.350
are capable of analyzing motion.

00:08:15.350 --> 00:08:17.740
That's a complex, very
interesting topic,

00:08:17.740 --> 00:08:19.820
as is depth perception.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:22.220
And the reason depth
perception is particularly

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:25.120
interesting is
because, as you know,

00:08:25.120 --> 00:08:27.560
the retinal surface
is essentially

00:08:27.560 --> 00:08:28.975
a two-dimensional arrangement.

00:08:30.030 --> 00:08:33.169
And yet from whatever falls
on these two dimensions

00:08:33.169 --> 00:08:36.010
in the left and right
eyes, somehow the brain

00:08:36.010 --> 00:08:40.270
needs to convert to be able
to see the third dimension.

00:08:40.270 --> 00:08:42.330
And as a result,
several mechanisms

00:08:42.330 --> 00:08:45.220
have evolved to
accomplish that, and we

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:47.620
are going to discuss them.

00:08:47.620 --> 00:08:49.930
Then, again, another
very complex topic

00:08:49.930 --> 00:08:52.400
is how we can recognize objects.

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:54.070
Perhaps the most
complex of those

00:08:54.070 --> 00:08:57.125
is our incredible ability
to recognize faces.

00:08:58.210 --> 00:09:00.560
And that is
highlighted, of course,

00:09:00.560 --> 00:09:03.910
by the fact that if you look
at more simple organisms,

00:09:03.910 --> 00:09:07.250
like, I don't know, monkeys,
they all look the same to you.

00:09:07.250 --> 00:09:08.710
But human beings,
who are actually

00:09:08.710 --> 00:09:11.930
more similar to each other
than perhaps monkeys are,

00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:13.750
we are really capable
of telling them

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:19.460
apart and readily recognize
them over long periods of time.

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:20.855
So it's a very
interesting topic.

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:25.000
And yet another topic
that we will discuss

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.220
is how we make eye movements.

00:09:27.220 --> 00:09:30.230
As you probably know,
or you're aware of,

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:32.450
that we are constantly
moving your eye.

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:35.560
You make saccadic eye movements
about three times a second,

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:39.290
thousands of times a day,
hundreds of thousands of times,

00:09:39.290 --> 00:09:42.980
to be able to see things
clearly in the world.

00:09:42.980 --> 00:09:44.730
So we are going to
try to understand

00:09:44.730 --> 00:09:48.490
how that incredible
ability has evolved

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:55.291
and how it is
realized by the brain.

00:09:55.291 --> 00:09:55.790
OK.

00:09:55.790 --> 00:09:59.390
So now to look at exactly how
