00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:45.080
All right.

00:11:45.080 --> 00:11:51.020
So now what I would like to talk
about next in a summary fashion

00:11:51.020 --> 00:11:53.320
are what we call the
tools of the trade.

00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:57.990
What has happened
over the many years

00:11:57.990 --> 00:11:59.740
that scientists
tried to understand

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:03.400
how the visual system and, for
that matter the brain, works,

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:06.800
what kinds of methods
have been employed.

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:09.560
And so I'm going to talk about
each of these just very briefly

00:12:09.560 --> 00:12:13.770
this time, and then they
will come up repeatedly

00:12:13.770 --> 00:12:15.320
during all of the lectures.

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:19.453
Now, the first method
I'm going to talk about

00:12:19.453 --> 00:12:20.453
is called psychophysics.

00:12:21.490 --> 00:12:23.435
I'm sure most of you
know what that is.

00:12:23.435 --> 00:12:30.530
It's a scientific way to study
behavior of humans and animals

00:12:30.530 --> 00:12:33.437
to determine how
well they can see.

00:12:33.437 --> 00:12:35.270
Now, there are several
procedures with this.

00:12:35.270 --> 00:12:37.950
I'm going to describe
one that's used

00:12:37.950 --> 00:12:39.760
both in humans and monkeys.

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:44.620
And what you can do nowadays,
you can use a color monitor,

00:12:44.620 --> 00:12:47.540
and I will describe
that in just a second.

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:49.920
After that, I will
talk about anatomy.

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:52.320
I will talk about
electrophysiology,

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:56.500
pharmacology, brain lesions,
imaging, and optogenetics.

00:12:57.630 --> 00:13:01.220
So now let's start with
psychophysics in more detail.

00:13:01.220 --> 00:13:06.060
So here is a color monitor,
and either monkeys or humans

00:13:06.060 --> 00:13:11.010
can be trained to first
look at a fixation spot.

00:13:11.010 --> 00:13:14.420
And that's important
because we want to always

00:13:14.420 --> 00:13:17.150
be able to present
stimuli in selected

00:13:17.150 --> 00:13:19.300
locations of the visual
field or selected

00:13:19.300 --> 00:13:21.700
locations along the retina.

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:23.920
This is particularly
important, because when

00:13:23.920 --> 00:13:29.950
you study the brain, different
regions of the visual field

00:13:29.950 --> 00:13:33.100
representation are located
in different areas,

00:13:33.100 --> 00:13:35.880
for example, in
the visual cortex.

00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:39.920
So what you do then is you
can present a single stimulus

00:13:39.920 --> 00:13:43.070
like this, and the task
of the human or the monkey

00:13:43.070 --> 00:13:45.600
is to either make a
saccadic eye movement to it,

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:47.740
say that's where
it is, or to press

00:13:47.740 --> 00:13:49.530
a lever that's in front of them.

00:13:51.410 --> 00:13:54.890
And then on each trial,
it appears someplace else.

00:13:54.890 --> 00:13:57.830
You can present it in
many different locations,

00:13:57.830 --> 00:13:59.590
and maybe one of
those locations will

00:13:59.590 --> 00:14:03.450
be relevant to what part of
the brain you are studying.

00:14:03.450 --> 00:14:06.040
And then what you do,
you can systematically

00:14:06.040 --> 00:14:09.130
vary all kinds of
aspects of the stimulus.

00:14:09.130 --> 00:14:10.590
You can vary the color.

00:14:10.590 --> 00:14:12.450
You can vary the contrast.

00:14:12.450 --> 00:14:14.160
You can vary the size.

00:14:14.160 --> 00:14:16.160
You can vary the shape.

00:14:16.160 --> 00:14:18.460
And by systematically
varying this,

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:24.730
you can create curves to
describe exactly how well you

00:14:24.730 --> 00:14:27.410
can see any
particular thing like,

00:14:27.410 --> 00:14:30.830
for example, just
how much contrast you

00:14:30.830 --> 00:14:32.150
need to perceive something.

00:14:33.340 --> 00:14:33.840
All right.

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:37.170
So that's called
the detection task.

00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:40.310
Now, a related task, which has
also been used extensively,

00:14:40.310 --> 00:14:42.540
is called the
discrimination task.

00:14:42.540 --> 00:14:46.090
In this case, you present
a fixation spot again.

00:14:46.090 --> 00:14:48.250
The person or the
monkey fixates,

00:14:48.250 --> 00:14:51.140
and then you present a whole
bunch of stimuli, one of which

00:14:51.140 --> 00:14:53.020
is different from the others.

00:14:53.020 --> 00:14:56.260
And you have to select
where that one had appeared,

00:14:56.260 --> 00:14:58.920
the one that's different,
by making an eye movement

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:01.120
or pressing the
appropriate lever.

00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:03.900
Now, when you do this,
you systematically

00:15:03.900 --> 00:15:09.040
can vary the difference between
the so-called distractor

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:10.880
stimuli, which
are all identical,

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:13.420
and the target
until the person is

00:15:13.420 --> 00:15:15.470
no longer able to
tell the difference.

00:15:15.470 --> 00:15:17.520
And that way you can,
again, generate a curve.

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:21.500
And you can specify just what
is the amount of difference

00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:24.500
that you need to
put in this, say,

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:29.400
how good are you at perceiving
slightly different colors.

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:30.880
All right?

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:33.110
And by doing that
systematically,

00:15:33.110 --> 00:15:36.430
you can generate
these functions using

00:15:36.430 --> 00:15:38.960
these psychophysical
procedures to determine

00:15:38.960 --> 00:15:42.800
pretty well how
you're able to see.

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:46.560
And now this particular
approach is also very useful

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:49.750
when it comes to studying
individuals, humans

00:15:49.750 --> 00:15:53.690
in this case, who have
some problems with vision.

00:15:53.690 --> 00:15:57.810
So if they have a
problem in seeing colors,

00:15:57.810 --> 00:16:02.300
you can readily
determine, well, what's

00:16:02.300 --> 00:16:03.640
the magnitude of that problem?

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:09.900
And thereby it can tell
you what procedures

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:15.210
might be used to try to
ameliorate their shortcoming.

00:16:15.210 --> 00:16:19.380
Now, another method that
has been used extensively

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:22.640
in not only vision, but in
many, many different areas

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:26.500
of studying the brain, including
audition of course, is anatomy.

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:34.610
Numerous methods have evolved
in the course of anatomists

00:16:34.610 --> 00:16:38.990
working on these problems, and
the first is a very simple one.

00:16:38.990 --> 00:16:41.190
You just look at
the whole brain.

00:16:41.190 --> 00:16:43.870
And I'm showing this because
this is a monkey brain,

00:16:43.870 --> 00:16:47.250
and you will encounter the
monkey brain repeatedly.

00:16:47.250 --> 00:16:50.730
And it so happens
that after people

00:16:50.730 --> 00:16:53.520
have studied this
extensively, they

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:55.610
were able to give
names to just about

00:16:55.610 --> 00:17:00.870
every gyrus or every brain
area and also relate it

00:17:00.870 --> 00:17:03.400
to what the function
is of those areas.

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:06.190
And so, for example, just
to name a few of these,

00:17:06.190 --> 00:17:08.349
this is called the
central sulcus.

00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:12.420
I need to do one
more thing here.

00:17:19.491 --> 00:17:19.990
OK.

00:17:19.990 --> 00:17:22.680
So this here is
the central sulcus.

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:23.280
All right?

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:25.690
Just for you to
remember, humans also

00:17:25.690 --> 00:17:27.710
have a central
sulcus, of course.

00:17:27.710 --> 00:17:30.230
And this is the lunate sulcus.

00:17:30.230 --> 00:17:33.720
And this region back here--
let's see, did I label this?

00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:37.685
Oh, here's a couple more, the
arcuate and the principalis.

00:17:37.685 --> 00:17:39.960
You will encounter
these repeatedly.

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:43.850
And this region
back here is the one

00:17:43.850 --> 00:17:50.100
which is the primary visual
cortex in monkeys that

00:17:50.100 --> 00:17:53.250
has been extensively
studied and has

00:17:53.250 --> 00:17:57.990
yielded remarkable discoveries
about the way it works.

00:17:57.990 --> 00:18:03.470
So that is called area V1,
or primary visual cortex.

00:18:03.470 --> 00:18:03.970
All right.

00:18:03.970 --> 00:18:06.600
So now just another
example, if I

00:18:06.600 --> 00:18:08.820
can show you just a few
examples of anatomy.

00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:13.520
Here's another example showing
what the eye looks like.

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:16.310
And the remarkable thing
about the human eye,

00:18:16.310 --> 00:18:19.280
and the eye of monkeys
as well and primates,

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:22.170
is it has become
highly specialized.

00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:25.890
There's a region here
which is called the fovea.

00:18:25.890 --> 00:18:32.140
And in that region, you have a
very, very dense distribution

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:36.080
of photoreceptors and
other cells in the retina.

00:18:36.080 --> 00:18:39.470
And because of that, you
have very high acuity there.

00:18:39.470 --> 00:18:43.180
Now, because of that,
the eye movements

00:18:43.180 --> 00:18:48.630
have to become effective for you
to be able to see fine detail.

00:18:49.840 --> 00:18:51.772
So even, for example,
when you read,

00:18:51.772 --> 00:18:52.980
what do you do when you read?

00:18:52.980 --> 00:18:55.490
You make saccadic eye
movements across a line.

00:18:55.490 --> 00:18:58.840
Then you go down the next line
three or four saccadic eye

00:18:58.840 --> 00:19:00.425
movements, and so
on down the page.

00:19:02.070 --> 00:19:05.690
And you do that because you
cannot make out the details

00:19:05.690 --> 00:19:09.100
of letters in the
periphery because, there,

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:13.810
the distribution of the
photoreceptors and the cells

00:19:13.810 --> 00:19:17.195
in the retina in general
become less and less dense.

00:19:18.640 --> 00:19:21.200
So that is a high
degree of specialization

00:19:21.200 --> 00:19:24.560
that we will discuss in
much more detail next time.

00:19:24.560 --> 00:19:27.980
Now then, all the fibers
from the retinal ganglion

00:19:27.980 --> 00:19:31.940
cells course across the
inner surface of the retina

00:19:31.940 --> 00:19:36.820
and go to the so-called
optic nerve through which

00:19:36.820 --> 00:19:40.370
over a million fibers
from the retina project

00:19:40.370 --> 00:19:44.070
into the nervous system.

00:19:44.070 --> 00:19:47.700
And how they project
exactly, what that's

00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:50.940
like I will discuss
in considerable detail

00:19:50.940 --> 00:19:52.170
the next time.

00:19:52.170 --> 00:19:55.600
Now, this area here
is often also called

00:19:55.600 --> 00:19:59.330
the blind spot,
and that you don't

00:19:59.330 --> 00:20:01.460
see even if you close one eye.

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:05.100
But if you do a
careful experiment--

00:20:05.100 --> 00:20:08.150
I'll explain that the next
time-- you can actually map out

00:20:08.150 --> 00:20:10.845
this little region where
you don't see anything.

00:20:11.850 --> 00:20:14.710
They're in different
locations in the two eyes,

00:20:14.710 --> 00:20:19.640
so the two blind
spots do not overlap.

00:20:19.640 --> 00:20:22.900
And so, consequently, when
you look with both eyes,

00:20:22.900 --> 00:20:25.590
you don't have a,
quote, blind spot.

00:20:25.590 --> 00:20:29.230
So that's an example of what
the human retina looks like,

00:20:29.230 --> 00:20:31.460
and this has been
studied extensively

00:20:31.460 --> 00:20:35.150
using a whole array of
anatomical procedures.

00:20:35.150 --> 00:20:39.610
Now, the third anatomical
procedure I want to tell you

00:20:39.610 --> 00:20:42.910
is labeling individual cells.

00:20:42.910 --> 00:20:46.640
Now, the way this was done,
or still is being done,

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:50.500
is that you slice the brain
into very, very thin sections.

00:20:50.500 --> 00:20:54.380
And you put them on
a glass, and then you

00:20:54.380 --> 00:20:56.440
can look at them
under a microscope.

00:20:56.440 --> 00:21:00.900
Now, here's an example of
a cross-coronal section

00:21:00.900 --> 00:21:03.430
of the monkey lateral
geniculate nucleus.

00:21:03.430 --> 00:21:06.170
That's one region in the brain
to which the retinal ganglion

00:21:06.170 --> 00:21:07.770
cells project.

00:21:07.770 --> 00:21:09.880
And it's a beautifully
layered structure,

00:21:09.880 --> 00:21:12.380
which I'll describe in
detail the next time.

00:21:12.380 --> 00:21:16.220
And these little spots
that you see here

00:21:16.220 --> 00:21:24.110
are actual cells, which are
labeled using a so-called Nissl

00:21:24.110 --> 00:21:24.610
stain.

00:21:25.720 --> 00:21:30.780
Now, another method
used in staining cells

00:21:30.780 --> 00:21:35.170
is the famous Golgi stain,
which was discovered, invented,

00:21:35.170 --> 00:21:38.370
perhaps, you could say, by
Golgi, for which he received

00:21:38.370 --> 00:21:41.010
the Nobel Prize in 1906.

00:21:41.010 --> 00:21:45.960
The remarkable quality
of those productions

00:21:45.960 --> 00:21:51.910
is that this label-- it's a
silver label-- stains not only

00:21:51.910 --> 00:21:55.260
the cell bodies, as the Nissl
stain you have just seen,

00:21:55.260 --> 00:22:00.520
but also all the processes, the
dendrites as well as the axons.

00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:03.430
So you see a whole
cell as a result

00:22:03.430 --> 00:22:05.590
of that staining procedure.

00:22:05.590 --> 00:22:08.370
Yet another way
to do this, which

00:22:08.370 --> 00:22:11.240
is more sophisticated
nowadays, is

00:22:11.240 --> 00:22:18.485
to record intracellularly from
a cell and then inject a label.

00:22:19.890 --> 00:22:23.605
This happens to be the so-called
Procion Yellow labeling

00:22:23.605 --> 00:22:24.105
substance.

00:22:24.105 --> 00:22:27.340
You inject in the eye, and then
you process the tissue again

00:22:27.340 --> 00:22:28.500
in thin layers.

00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:31.330
And this is an example
of what that looks like.

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:35.260
So this also stains all
the processes of the cell.

00:22:35.260 --> 00:22:37.290
And the advantage
here is that you

00:22:37.290 --> 00:22:40.310
can study this cell
electrophysiologically

00:22:40.310 --> 00:22:42.520
and determine what
it is like, and then

00:22:42.520 --> 00:22:45.050
stain it so you can establish
the relationship what

00:22:45.050 --> 00:22:48.451
the cell does and what
the cell looks like.

00:22:48.451 --> 00:22:48.950
All right.

00:22:48.950 --> 00:22:53.270
So now let's turn to the
electrophysiological method,

00:22:53.270 --> 00:22:58.320
which is a consequence of this,
logical consequence of it.

00:22:58.320 --> 00:23:00.900
Once again, here we
have a monkey brain.

00:23:00.900 --> 00:23:07.170
And what you do here, we put
microelectrodes into the brain.

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:09.310
Now, this was a
discovery that was

00:23:09.310 --> 00:23:12.470
made around the turn of the
century, little bit after.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.160
Initially,
microelectrodes were made

00:23:17.160 --> 00:23:21.260
from very thin tubes of
glass, which were heated

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:25.485
and then pulled so that the tip
became smaller than a micron.

00:23:26.730 --> 00:23:28.200
So it was very, very small.

00:23:28.200 --> 00:23:30.205
Subsequently, other
methods were developed.

00:23:31.715 --> 00:23:36.870
They etched fine pieces a wire
until the tip was very, very

00:23:36.870 --> 00:23:39.170
small, and then they corded it.

00:23:39.170 --> 00:23:43.880
And they then we were able
to put these electrodes

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:48.440
into the brain and record single
cells just like with glass

00:23:48.440 --> 00:23:49.600
pipettes.

00:23:49.600 --> 00:23:54.420
So the example here then is
that you take a microelectrode,

00:23:54.420 --> 00:23:57.700
put it into the brain,
and then that is connected

00:23:57.700 --> 00:24:03.430
to an amplifier
system and a computer.

00:24:03.430 --> 00:24:07.980
And when you do that, you can
record from a single cell.

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:10.500
Now, as you well
know, single cells

00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:13.755
generate action potentials.

00:24:14.970 --> 00:24:17.850
And that is shown here
on an oscilloscope

00:24:17.850 --> 00:24:19.800
in a schematic fashion.

00:24:19.800 --> 00:24:22.930
And what some
clever people did is

00:24:22.930 --> 00:24:29.720
that they decided that an easy
way to process information

00:24:29.720 --> 00:24:35.420
about the manner
single cells generated

00:24:35.420 --> 00:24:39.990
action potentials is to put
this signal onto a loudspeaker

00:24:39.990 --> 00:24:41.080
system.

00:24:41.080 --> 00:24:44.020
And so every time a cell fired,
what you would literally hear

00:24:44.020 --> 00:24:45.700
is beep, beep, like that.

00:24:45.700 --> 00:24:46.400
OK?

00:24:46.400 --> 00:24:50.720
And so if you shown a
light on it several times,

00:24:50.720 --> 00:24:52.770
it will go like
brrrp, like that.

00:24:52.770 --> 00:24:55.300
And the big
advantage of this was

00:24:55.300 --> 00:24:58.284
that many cells see only a
tiny portion of the world.

00:24:58.284 --> 00:24:59.700
And if you don't
know where it is,

00:24:59.700 --> 00:25:02.980
you have to take some
projector or something

00:25:02.980 --> 00:25:04.190
and move it around.

00:25:04.190 --> 00:25:05.875
And if the receptive
field is here,

00:25:05.875 --> 00:25:10.040
you go, brrrp, brrrp,
brrrp, brrrp, like that.

00:25:10.040 --> 00:25:10.550
OK?

00:25:10.550 --> 00:25:13.090
And so then you can map
it out very accurately.

00:25:13.090 --> 00:25:16.370
Instead of having to like with
the oscilloscope, you hear it,

00:25:16.370 --> 00:25:21.180
and that enables you to do all
kinds of things, experiments,

00:25:21.180 --> 00:25:23.435
and you don't have to
look at the oscilloscope.

00:25:23.435 --> 00:25:25.310
But you can perform all
sorts of experiments,

00:25:25.310 --> 00:25:29.240
and you can hear the
responses of the cell.

00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:32.250
Now, another method
that is used extensively

00:25:32.250 --> 00:25:37.570
in electrophysiology is
called electrical stimulation.

00:25:37.570 --> 00:25:38.800
It's a similar process.

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:41.540
You take a microelectrode,
for example, you

00:25:41.540 --> 00:25:48.610
put it in the brain, and then
you pass electric current.

00:25:48.610 --> 00:25:52.120
Typically, that electric current
is passed in such a way as

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:54.360
to mimic action potentials.

00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:58.380
So if you are to listen to when
it's activated, again, brrrp,

00:25:58.380 --> 00:25:59.780
you hear that.

00:25:59.780 --> 00:26:02.110
But this time, instead
of the cell firing,

00:26:02.110 --> 00:26:06.740
you are firing the area
there, and that then

00:26:06.740 --> 00:26:11.170
can elicit a response, all
right, all kinds of responses.

00:26:11.170 --> 00:26:15.040
If you stimulate here, for
example-- remember now,

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:18.380
this is the visual
system in the monkey-- as

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:22.480
has been shown in humans,
electrical stimulation elicits

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:25.390
a percept, a small
spot, a star-like image.

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:28.730
In the auditory system
when you stimulate,

00:26:28.730 --> 00:26:29.835
you can hear something.

00:26:31.820 --> 00:26:38.020
And if you stimulate
in the areas that

00:26:38.020 --> 00:26:42.690
are related to moving your
eyes, then the simulation

00:26:42.690 --> 00:26:44.870
causes a saccadic eye movement.

00:26:44.870 --> 00:26:47.790
So all those methods
are very, very good

00:26:47.790 --> 00:26:54.950
in trying to understand better
the organization of the brain

00:26:54.950 --> 00:27:00.940
for, in this case for vision,
and for eye movements.

00:27:02.030 --> 00:27:04.320
Now, yet another
method that is used--

00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:07.740
several methods I should
say-- is pharmacology.

00:27:07.740 --> 00:27:12.230
And when you do
pharmacological experiments,

00:27:12.230 --> 00:27:14.830
one procedure is-- and
many different procedures,

00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:17.640
I'll just describe
one here-- once again,

00:27:17.640 --> 00:27:23.000
you can stick a glass
pipette into the brain,

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:24.960
and then you can inject it.

00:27:24.960 --> 00:27:28.200
You can inject it either
with actually a syringe

00:27:28.200 --> 00:27:30.510
or using several
other methods, and you

00:27:30.510 --> 00:27:32.600
can inject all kinds of agents.

00:27:32.600 --> 00:27:36.840
For example, you can inject
a neurotransmitter analog

00:27:36.840 --> 00:27:42.270
or a neurotransmitter antagonist
to determine what effects it

00:27:42.270 --> 00:27:46.130
has in various parts of
the brain and, in our case,

00:27:46.130 --> 00:27:50.270
in the visual system or
the ocular motor system.

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:54.140
Now, yet another method
that has been used

00:27:54.140 --> 00:27:56.855
is brain inactivation.

00:27:58.340 --> 00:28:03.285
Several procedures are available
to inactivate the brain.

00:28:05.410 --> 00:28:06.940
Once again, here's
a monkey brain.

00:28:08.300 --> 00:28:10.170
And this region
here that I already

00:28:10.170 --> 00:28:12.950
told you a little
bit about because

00:28:12.950 --> 00:28:19.870
of naming the gyri there, OK, is
called the frontal eye fields.

00:28:19.870 --> 00:28:23.910
This region has something
to do with moving your eyes.

00:28:23.910 --> 00:28:27.390
So what you can do if you
want to study and find out

00:28:27.390 --> 00:28:30.240
just what does this
area do, one procedure

00:28:30.240 --> 00:28:34.265
is to-- again, here is
V1-- is to make a lesion.

00:28:35.971 --> 00:28:38.880
Now, sometimes you actually
do that in a monkey.

00:28:38.880 --> 00:28:41.570
But sometimes in
some experiments,

00:28:41.570 --> 00:28:49.160
humans may have an
accident, some event when

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:51.700
you served in
Vietnam or something,

00:28:51.700 --> 00:28:55.230
and a region of
the brain has been

00:28:55.230 --> 00:28:57.860
removed by virtue of
a bullet or something.

00:28:57.860 --> 00:29:00.700
And that way you
can find out what

00:29:00.700 --> 00:29:04.830
is the consequence of
having a lesion like that.

00:29:04.830 --> 00:29:07.120
You can study, use a
psychophysical procedure,

00:29:07.120 --> 00:29:11.570
as I described to
you, to determine just

00:29:11.570 --> 00:29:15.050
what is the consequence
of having lost this area.

00:29:15.050 --> 00:29:17.750
This is a huge
region of research.

00:29:17.750 --> 00:29:20.930
A great many types of
experiments have been done.

00:29:20.930 --> 00:29:24.180
One of the famous individuals
who had done this kind of work

00:29:24.180 --> 00:29:27.830
is Hans-Lukas Teuber,
who used to be

00:29:27.830 --> 00:29:31.430
the chairman of our department
starting way, way, way

00:29:31.430 --> 00:29:33.790
back in 1962.

00:29:33.790 --> 00:29:40.320
And his specialty was to study
Second World War veterans who

00:29:40.320 --> 00:29:43.370
had sustained various
kinds of brain injuries.

00:29:43.370 --> 00:29:45.480
And the basis of
that, studying them

00:29:45.480 --> 00:29:52.280
using psychophysical
procedures, to assess what

00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:57.990
various areas in the brain, what
kind of functions they have,

00:29:57.990 --> 00:30:00.950
what kinds of tasks
do they perform.

00:30:00.950 --> 00:30:05.550
Now, yet another method, which
has some major advantages,

00:30:05.550 --> 00:30:08.940
is to make reversible
inactivations rather than

00:30:08.940 --> 00:30:09.890
permanent ones.

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:14.640
And this you can
do by, for example,

00:30:14.640 --> 00:30:16.590
using a method of cooling.

00:30:16.590 --> 00:30:19.810
There's a device, the
so-called Peltier device,

00:30:19.810 --> 00:30:22.430
that you can put on
top of the brain.

00:30:22.430 --> 00:30:26.410
And then electronically, you
can cool the surface that

00:30:26.410 --> 00:30:28.880
is in touch with
the brain, and then

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:31.050
you can see what happens
when you cool it.

00:30:31.050 --> 00:30:33.920
And then when you
warm it up again,

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:38.000
you can see what happens to
recovery, which, in this case,

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.740
in almost all cases
like this, leads

00:30:40.740 --> 00:30:43.645
to full recovery and
the same performance

00:30:43.645 --> 00:30:46.540
as prior to starting
the cooling.

00:30:46.540 --> 00:30:47.040
Yes?

00:30:47.040 --> 00:30:50.310
AUDIENCE: Can you only use this
method for surface structures

00:30:50.310 --> 00:30:50.810
or?

00:30:50.810 --> 00:30:51.780
PROFESSOR: No.

00:30:51.780 --> 00:30:54.590
They have now developed
methods where you can actually

00:30:54.590 --> 00:30:57.190
lower them into the brain.

00:30:57.190 --> 00:31:02.250
And they're usually much
finer, and very often they're

00:31:02.250 --> 00:31:05.060
sort of a loop type device.

00:31:05.060 --> 00:31:08.560
And you can lower that into
the gyri or wherever you like,

00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:10.661
and, again, do the
reversible cooling.

00:31:10.661 --> 00:31:11.160
Yes.

00:31:12.162 --> 00:31:15.230
That's a fairly recently
developed device,

00:31:15.230 --> 00:31:17.115
and it works extremely well.

00:31:17.115 --> 00:31:21.370
Now, yet another approach
is to inject substances

00:31:21.370 --> 00:31:25.200
into the brain that
anesthetize, if you will,

00:31:25.200 --> 00:31:29.000
a particular region
after the injection,

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.450
but only for a limited time.

00:31:31.450 --> 00:31:36.790
And then you can see how
the behavior is affected.

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:39.490
Now, a variant of
that that I referred

00:31:39.490 --> 00:31:44.040
to before, of course, is
that you can use agents that

00:31:44.040 --> 00:31:48.790
are selective, that don't
inactivate the whole area,

00:31:48.790 --> 00:31:57.360
but for example, only affect
excitatory neurotransmitters

00:31:57.360 --> 00:31:59.570
or only affect inhibitory ones.

00:31:59.570 --> 00:32:01.790
So you can do kinds
of selective things.

00:32:01.790 --> 00:32:04.490
And so you can
establish the role

00:32:04.490 --> 00:32:09.120
of various neurotransmitters
in the role

00:32:09.120 --> 00:32:12.990
they play in
various brain areas.

00:32:12.990 --> 00:32:17.270
Now, yet another method
very recently developed,

00:32:17.270 --> 00:32:20.025
which has been incredibly
successful, is imaging.

00:32:21.320 --> 00:32:23.230
As you probably
all know, you all

00:32:23.230 --> 00:32:28.550
know we do have an
MRI facility here

00:32:28.550 --> 00:32:31.270
in our department on the
ground floor, and some of you

00:32:31.270 --> 00:32:33.850
may even have been
subjects in it.

00:32:33.850 --> 00:32:37.100
What that does is
when you put a subject

00:32:37.100 --> 00:32:39.480
into this-- the variant
of that is called

00:32:39.480 --> 00:32:43.470
fMRI, functional Magnetic
Resonance Imaging.

00:32:43.470 --> 00:32:45.980
And so if you put a person
in the magnet and you present

00:32:45.980 --> 00:32:50.700
a certain set of
stimuli repeatedly, OK,

00:32:50.700 --> 00:32:55.340
or differential ones,
whatever, the brain areas

00:32:55.340 --> 00:32:58.710
that are active
performing the analysis

00:32:58.710 --> 00:33:03.050
that you ask them
to do light up.

00:33:04.330 --> 00:33:08.620
So that method-- here's a
complex picture of that.

00:33:08.620 --> 00:33:11.030
This is one that is
in Freiberg, Germany.

00:33:12.370 --> 00:33:14.510
This is done with monkeys again.

00:33:14.510 --> 00:33:16.830
You have this device and
you put the monkey in there.

00:33:16.830 --> 00:33:19.820
You lower the device
on it, and then you

00:33:19.820 --> 00:33:24.890
can have the subject
perform trained tasks.

00:33:24.890 --> 00:33:26.820
And then you can
analyze the brain

00:33:26.820 --> 00:33:29.120
and look at the
nature of activation.

00:33:29.120 --> 00:33:31.530
And here's an example
of that, whatever

00:33:31.530 --> 00:33:33.310
this task is, doesn't matter.

00:33:33.310 --> 00:33:34.890
You can see that
a particular brain

00:33:34.890 --> 00:33:37.580
region has been very
heavily activated

00:33:37.580 --> 00:33:40.780
as a result of whatever
manipulation they did.

00:33:40.780 --> 00:33:43.780
Now, there are lots and
lots and lots of experiments

00:33:43.780 --> 00:33:46.960
of this sort, and we will
talk about several of those

00:33:46.960 --> 00:33:50.960
as we look at various
aspects of the visual system.

00:33:50.960 --> 00:33:54.870
Now, the last method I want to
just mention very, very briefly

00:33:54.870 --> 00:33:56.310
is optogenetics.

00:33:56.310 --> 00:33:59.040
That's a new method, and we
have actually several people

00:33:59.040 --> 00:34:02.510
in our department here
who are using this method.

00:34:02.510 --> 00:34:05.460
Now, this particular
method-- let

00:34:05.460 --> 00:34:09.285
me explain just very quickly
what this is all about.

00:34:12.010 --> 00:34:13.870
Does everybody know
what an opsin is?

00:34:15.030 --> 00:34:15.530
OK.

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:16.738
How about if I say rhodopsin?

00:34:17.989 --> 00:34:18.610
OK.

00:34:18.610 --> 00:34:19.795
Most of you will know that.

00:34:19.795 --> 00:34:23.770
A rhodopsin is a
set of molecules

00:34:23.770 --> 00:34:27.780
that are in the rods
in the photoreceptors,

00:34:27.780 --> 00:34:29.579
and they are sensitive to light.

00:34:29.579 --> 00:34:31.120
Now, there are all
kinds of variants.

00:34:31.120 --> 00:34:33.774
That's why I mentioned opsins
rather than rhodopsins.

00:34:35.190 --> 00:34:39.960
And what can be done is
that you can selectivity

00:34:39.960 --> 00:34:44.989
place these various substances
into selected types of cells

00:34:44.989 --> 00:34:46.489
in the brain.

00:34:46.489 --> 00:34:52.370
And then, because these cells
become light sensitive just

00:34:52.370 --> 00:34:58.670
like the photoreceptors are,
then when you shine light

00:34:58.670 --> 00:35:09.150
onto the area where you had
placed these opsins in cells,

00:35:09.150 --> 00:35:10.360
you can drive them.

00:35:10.360 --> 00:35:14.120
You can make them respond
by turning the light on.

00:35:14.120 --> 00:35:16.130
Now, the amazing
thing about that

00:35:16.130 --> 00:35:18.600
is that makes it a
more powerful technique

00:35:18.600 --> 00:35:22.010
than electrical stimulation,
that you can set this up

00:35:22.010 --> 00:35:33.040
in such a way that, for
example, if you use a rhodopsin

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:39.010
substance that is
sensitive to red light,

00:35:39.010 --> 00:35:43.560
it will be excited
by the red light.

00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:49.810
But if you have a slightly
different substance that

00:35:49.810 --> 00:35:52.220
would be inhibited
by blue light,

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:55.020
then you can see what happens
if you excite those cells,

00:35:55.020 --> 00:35:56.910
and then you
inhibit those cells.

00:35:56.910 --> 00:36:00.210
So this gives you two
sides to the coin,

00:36:00.210 --> 00:36:03.340
whereas electrical stimulation
provides only one side.

00:36:03.340 --> 00:36:04.970
So that's a wonderful technique.

00:36:04.970 --> 00:36:08.200
And here's sort of a
good example of that.

00:36:08.200 --> 00:36:11.650
Here we have
injected-- I shouldn't

00:36:11.650 --> 00:36:15.980
say injected-- but
genetically labeled

00:36:15.980 --> 00:36:20.490
cells with
channelrhodopsin, so-called.

00:36:20.490 --> 00:36:24.700
And when that's done, when
you shine in a blue light,

00:36:24.700 --> 00:36:27.340
OK, you excite the cell.

00:36:27.340 --> 00:36:33.120
And then instead, if you put
in so-called halorhodopsin, OK,

00:36:33.120 --> 00:36:36.130
halorhodopsin, then if
you use yellow light

00:36:36.130 --> 00:36:37.970
you inhibit the cells.

00:36:37.970 --> 00:36:39.560
So that's a
remarkable technique.

00:36:40.820 --> 00:36:43.520
It's just at the very
beginning of things,

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:46.430
so we won't talk too
much about this technique

00:36:46.430 --> 00:36:48.400
in studying the
visual system yet.

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:50.930
But I bet you that
in another 10 years

00:36:50.930 --> 00:36:52.870
this is going to
be a central topic.

00:36:52.870 --> 00:36:53.370
All right.

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:55.520
So to summarize
these techniques,

00:36:55.520 --> 00:36:59.730
other than the psychophysics,
just remind you again,

00:36:59.730 --> 00:37:02.444
number one, we have
electrical recording

00:37:02.444 --> 00:37:03.360
using microelectrodes.

00:37:05.300 --> 00:37:05.940
OK?

00:37:05.940 --> 00:37:08.325
Then secondly, we have
electrical stimulation.

00:37:09.420 --> 00:37:14.110
Thirdly, we have injection
of pharmacological agent.

00:37:14.110 --> 00:37:18.140
Then we have methods
to inactivate regions,

00:37:18.140 --> 00:37:21.420
either permanently by lesions
or reversibly by cooling

00:37:21.420 --> 00:37:24.320
or by injecting
various substances.

00:37:24.320 --> 00:37:27.030
And lastly, we have
optogenetics that

00:37:27.030 --> 00:37:31.200
enables you to activate
cells or inhibit cells

00:37:31.200 --> 00:37:34.760
by shining light onto the brain.

00:37:34.760 --> 00:37:38.480
So these are quite a
remarkable set of techniques.

00:37:38.480 --> 00:37:44.060
And individuals who want
to become neuroscientists,

00:37:44.060 --> 00:37:46.960
they're going to have to
learn to master not maybe

00:37:46.960 --> 00:37:49.390
all of these techniques,
but certainly some of them

00:37:49.390 --> 00:37:52.880
so that they can carry out
new and original experiments

00:37:52.880 --> 00:37:55.990
in determining how
the brain works

00:37:55.990 --> 00:37:59.070
and, in our case, of course,
how the visual system works.

00:37:59.070 --> 00:38:02.390
So that is, in essence then,
