In the second lecture, we'll
be talking about the receptor

00:45:54.390 --> 00:45:57.940
cells for hearing, which are
called hair cells because they

00:45:57.940 --> 00:45:59.930
have these little
appendages at their top

00:45:59.930 --> 00:46:04.360
that looked to the early
neuroanatomists like hairs.

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:07.970
And of course, sound
is a mechanical energy

00:46:07.970 --> 00:46:11.760
that moves the fluid in which
these hair cells are immersed

00:46:11.760 --> 00:46:14.220
and moves these little
hairs or appendages

00:46:14.220 --> 00:46:16.100
at the top of the
cell, and that's

00:46:16.100 --> 00:46:19.650
how the cell can
respond then to sound.

00:46:19.650 --> 00:46:23.040
And so hair cells are the
very important receptor cells

00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:27.070
for hearing, which are, of
course, the analogs of the rods

00:46:27.070 --> 00:46:28.665
and cones in the visual system.

00:46:29.770 --> 00:46:32.300
And the research
report associated

00:46:32.300 --> 00:46:35.630
with our talk about
hair cells will

00:46:35.630 --> 00:46:40.500
be how a special protein
called prestin is required

00:46:40.500 --> 00:46:44.330
for electromotility, which
is a function of outer hair

00:46:44.330 --> 00:46:47.040
cells, one of the two
types of hair cells,

00:46:47.040 --> 00:46:51.360
which allows them to actually
move and flux and change

00:46:51.360 --> 00:46:54.560
their membrane links
when they sense

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:57.950
these mechanical disturbances
by their stereocilia.

00:46:57.950 --> 00:47:01.025
So it's a pretty
interesting paper

00:47:01.025 --> 00:47:03.740
in what we call a
knockout animal.

00:47:03.740 --> 00:47:06.760
So the prestin is
genetically knocked out

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:09.910
in this particular animal,
and the sense of hearing

00:47:09.910 --> 00:47:12.650
is then tested again in
these knockout animals.

00:47:14.730 --> 00:47:16.930
So we have a whole
bunch of lectures.

00:47:16.930 --> 00:47:19.441
I haven't indicated all them.

00:47:19.441 --> 00:47:20.690
They're on the course website.

00:47:22.210 --> 00:47:25.900
Toward the end of the semester,
we'll have, as Peter indicated,

00:47:25.900 --> 00:47:28.410
a written assignment
for audition.

00:47:28.410 --> 00:47:33.510
So I haven't actually
thought it up yet,

00:47:33.510 --> 00:47:35.940
but let me just
give you an example.

00:47:35.940 --> 00:47:40.160
Last year and this year,
we'll be talking a lot

00:47:40.160 --> 00:47:42.900
about neural prostheses
for audition.

00:47:42.900 --> 00:47:46.140
And the most famous neural
prosthesis for audition,

00:47:46.140 --> 00:47:47.892
of course, is the
cochlear implant,

00:47:47.892 --> 00:47:49.600
which I'll talk a
little bit about later,

00:47:49.600 --> 00:47:50.860
and it works quite well.

00:47:52.280 --> 00:47:54.430
There's also a neural
prosthesis that

00:47:54.430 --> 00:47:56.790
goes into the
auditory brainstem.

00:47:56.790 --> 00:47:59.390
It's called the auditory
brainstem implant,

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:01.640
and it's used in
some other types

00:48:01.640 --> 00:48:03.760
of individuals who are deaf.

00:48:03.760 --> 00:48:06.870
And it doesn't work anywhere
near as well as the cochlear

00:48:06.870 --> 00:48:07.710
implant.

00:48:07.710 --> 00:48:11.580
It's sometimes called a
lip reading assist device

00:48:11.580 --> 00:48:14.570
because people who have
the brainstem implant

00:48:14.570 --> 00:48:17.960
usually can't understand
speech over the telephone.

00:48:17.960 --> 00:48:20.900
They need to be facing you
and looking at your lips

00:48:20.900 --> 00:48:22.370
as you're speaking.

00:48:22.370 --> 00:48:24.460
They need additional cues.

00:48:24.460 --> 00:48:26.965
And so there'll be
a lot of discussion

00:48:26.965 --> 00:48:29.840
this term about the
differences between these two

00:48:29.840 --> 00:48:31.440
types of the implant,
where they're

00:48:31.440 --> 00:48:34.315
put in the auditory
pathway, and why

00:48:34.315 --> 00:48:37.110
one works much better
than the other.

00:48:37.110 --> 00:48:38.830
And that was the
written assignment

00:48:38.830 --> 00:48:43.800
for last year, which was a
discussion of why the cochlear

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:46.725
implant works a lot better than
the auditory brainstem implant.

00:48:46.725 --> 00:48:50.260
So I'll have something
along those lines that

00:48:50.260 --> 00:48:52.920
uses the material
from our course

00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:55.370
that you can take to
answer a question.

00:49:00.330 --> 00:49:00.830
OK.

00:49:00.830 --> 00:49:04.380
Let me just go through in
a half a dozen slides or so

00:49:04.380 --> 00:49:06.230
what I consider to
be the high points

00:49:06.230 --> 00:49:08.805
of the auditory
part of the course.

00:49:09.820 --> 00:49:13.030
About the first third of the
auditory part of the course

00:49:13.030 --> 00:49:15.520
will be a discussion of
the auditory periphery.

00:49:16.750 --> 00:49:19.200
And the periphery
is usually divided

00:49:19.200 --> 00:49:24.230
into these three basic
divisions, the external ear,

00:49:24.230 --> 00:49:28.360
which most of us think about as
the ear, the pinna and the ear

00:49:28.360 --> 00:49:33.010
canal, which leads to
the tympanic membrane

00:49:33.010 --> 00:49:34.545
here in yellow, or eardrum.

00:49:36.150 --> 00:49:39.740
And at that point
begins the middle ear.

00:49:39.740 --> 00:49:41.705
The middle ear is
an air-filled space.

00:49:42.915 --> 00:49:45.110
If you've been on a
recent plane flight

00:49:45.110 --> 00:49:47.630
and your ears are a
little bit stuffed up,

00:49:47.630 --> 00:49:50.020
it can be very uncomfortable,
especially when

00:49:50.020 --> 00:49:52.930
the plane is coming
down in altitude.

00:49:52.930 --> 00:49:56.010
And your eardrum bulges
because the eardrum is just

00:49:56.010 --> 00:50:00.080
a very thin layer of skin,
and it can bulge very easily.

00:50:00.080 --> 00:50:02.400
But it's painful
when the eardrum

00:50:02.400 --> 00:50:05.170
bulges when the
change in pressure

00:50:05.170 --> 00:50:07.060
happens as you're
descending in a plane.

00:50:08.830 --> 00:50:11.560
In the air-filled
space of the middle ear

00:50:11.560 --> 00:50:16.420
are three small bones,
the malleus, the incus,

00:50:16.420 --> 00:50:17.620
and the stapes.

00:50:17.620 --> 00:50:22.590
If you remember from high school
biology, the hammer, the anvil,

00:50:22.590 --> 00:50:23.640
and the stirrup.

00:50:23.640 --> 00:50:26.950
The stirrup looks like what
a cowboy has on his saddle

00:50:26.950 --> 00:50:29.820
that he puts the
cowboy boots through.

00:50:29.820 --> 00:50:31.530
It's a very, very small bone.

00:50:31.530 --> 00:50:33.820
In fact, it's the
smallest bone in the body.

00:50:35.406 --> 00:50:37.030
These bones are very
small because they

00:50:37.030 --> 00:50:39.950
have to vibrate in
response to sound,

00:50:39.950 --> 00:50:41.740
and so they can't
be big and massive.

00:50:41.740 --> 00:50:43.870
Massive things don't
vibrate very well.

00:50:45.140 --> 00:50:53.230
And so the stapes is sometimes
encompassed by bony growths

00:50:53.230 --> 00:50:56.320
around it and prevented
from vibration

00:50:56.320 --> 00:50:57.920
in a disease called
otosclerosis.

00:50:59.430 --> 00:51:01.625
And so at my hospital,
the Massachusetts Eye

00:51:01.625 --> 00:51:04.370
and Ear Infirmary,
they do an operation

00:51:04.370 --> 00:51:08.280
to cure that type of deafness
called the stapedectomy.

00:51:08.280 --> 00:51:09.770
So what's an -ectomy?

00:51:09.770 --> 00:51:12.116
You medical types,
what does that mean?

00:51:12.116 --> 00:51:12.930
AUDIENCE: Removal.

00:51:12.930 --> 00:51:14.388
PROFESSOR: It means
removal, right.

00:51:14.388 --> 00:51:15.790
So they take the stapes out.

00:51:16.850 --> 00:51:19.330
And that's because if
they just loosen it up,

00:51:19.330 --> 00:51:23.210
the bone regrows and re-adheres
the stapes from vibration.

00:51:23.210 --> 00:51:26.920
So they replace the
stapes, the natural stapes,

00:51:26.920 --> 00:51:32.160
with a stapes prosthesis, either
a little piston or a tube,

00:51:32.160 --> 00:51:35.740
that they hook on with
a wire to the incus,

00:51:35.740 --> 00:51:39.850
and they put into the so-called
foot plate area or oval

00:51:39.850 --> 00:51:42.840
window of the cochlea, which
is the next structure I'll

00:51:42.840 --> 00:51:44.060
talk about.

00:51:44.060 --> 00:51:47.440
And that very nicely restores
the sense of hearing.

00:51:47.440 --> 00:51:51.046
In fact, when I was a postdoc
fellow at Mass Eye and Ear,

00:51:51.046 --> 00:51:54.890
I could go watch the surgeries,
and I watched a stapedectomy.

00:51:54.890 --> 00:51:57.970
And the patient was
anesthetized, but not

00:51:57.970 --> 00:52:00.380
so much that she was really out.

00:52:00.380 --> 00:52:01.550
She was more sedated.

00:52:02.560 --> 00:52:04.690
And at the end of the
operation, the surgeon

00:52:04.690 --> 00:52:08.050
was adjusting the
artificial prosthesis,

00:52:08.050 --> 00:52:10.710
and the surgeon said,
well, can you hear me?

00:52:10.710 --> 00:52:12.900
And the patient didn't respond.

00:52:12.900 --> 00:52:15.720
So he moved it around a little
bit or adjusted the wire,

00:52:15.720 --> 00:52:16.800
I don't know which.

00:52:16.800 --> 00:52:18.350
He says, can you hear me now?

00:52:18.350 --> 00:52:21.180
And there was no response
from the patient.

00:52:21.180 --> 00:52:23.510
And he did a little more
manipulation and adjustment.

00:52:23.510 --> 00:52:25.480
And he finally said,
can you hear me?

00:52:25.480 --> 00:52:27.500
And the patient said, why
are you yelling at me?

00:52:27.500 --> 00:52:28.605
I can hear you just fine.

00:52:29.710 --> 00:52:31.680
So usually at the
end of the operation,

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:34.320
the patient has
become more light.

00:52:34.320 --> 00:52:36.860
The anesthesiologist
turns off the anesthesia.

00:52:36.860 --> 00:52:40.930
And they adjust the stapes
prosthesis so it works well.

00:52:42.420 --> 00:52:46.530
So that type of operation
is fairly common

00:52:46.530 --> 00:52:50.640
and very successful to
restore the so-called types

00:52:50.640 --> 00:52:52.250
of conductive hearing loss.

00:52:52.250 --> 00:52:56.735
These bones conduct the acoustic
sensation into the cochlea.

00:52:57.920 --> 00:53:02.570
Now, in the cochlea-- this
is the structure here.

00:53:02.570 --> 00:53:05.180
The "cochlea" is the
word for the inner ear.

00:53:05.180 --> 00:53:09.770
It comes from the Greek word
"kokhlias," which means snail,

00:53:09.770 --> 00:53:14.570
and it is certainly a
snail shell-shaped capsule.

00:53:14.570 --> 00:53:18.510
The cochlea looks like
a coiled snail shell.

00:53:18.510 --> 00:53:22.650
And inside it are
the receptor cells

00:53:22.650 --> 00:53:25.690
for hearing, the hair
cells and the dendrites

00:53:25.690 --> 00:53:27.700
of the auditory nerve fibers.

00:53:27.700 --> 00:53:28.200
OK?

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:31.930
And the cochlea is a
bony-filled capsule

00:53:31.930 --> 00:53:35.025
filled with fluid and
membranes and cells inside.

00:53:36.250 --> 00:53:38.600
And this anatomy is
a little bit complex,

00:53:38.600 --> 00:53:41.970
so I brought in a model here
of the auditory periphery.

00:53:41.970 --> 00:53:45.960
So we have the external
ear, the long ear canal

00:53:45.960 --> 00:53:47.430
here, the eardrum.

00:53:47.430 --> 00:53:50.220
It's kind of slanted here.

00:53:50.220 --> 00:53:52.850
And this part here
that I'll lift out here

00:53:52.850 --> 00:53:58.010
is the cochlea or the inner ear,
the snail shell-shaped area.

00:53:58.010 --> 00:54:01.650
And leading from it is the
yellow-colored, in this case,

00:54:01.650 --> 00:54:05.470
auditory nerve, which sends
messages from the cochlea

00:54:05.470 --> 00:54:07.160
into the brain.

00:54:07.160 --> 00:54:10.790
And these funny, loop-shaped
structures that I'm grasping

00:54:10.790 --> 00:54:15.450
are the semicircular
canals, which

00:54:15.450 --> 00:54:18.336
mediate the sense of balance
or angular acceleration.

00:54:19.390 --> 00:54:22.610
When you rotate your head,
those hair cells in there

00:54:22.610 --> 00:54:24.625
are sensitive to
those rotations.

00:54:25.980 --> 00:54:26.480
OK.

00:54:26.480 --> 00:54:28.380
So I'll pass this model around.

00:54:28.380 --> 00:54:30.760
You can take a
closer look at it.

00:54:30.760 --> 00:54:35.830
And in our hospital,
the surgeons practice

00:54:35.830 --> 00:54:41.620
on real, live specimens like
that from postmortem material

00:54:41.620 --> 00:54:44.440
because in otologic
surgery there's

00:54:44.440 --> 00:54:49.150
a lot of drilling to access,
for example, the middle ear

00:54:49.150 --> 00:54:50.960
or the inner ear.

00:54:50.960 --> 00:54:53.680
And there's a lot of
important structures

00:54:53.680 --> 00:54:56.210
that you don't want to run
into with your drill bit,

00:54:56.210 --> 00:54:59.880
like the jugular bulb
is that red thing there.

00:54:59.880 --> 00:55:03.620
The facial nerve goes right
through the middle ear.

00:55:03.620 --> 00:55:07.030
And so the surgeons need to know
their way around the middle ear

00:55:07.030 --> 00:55:09.700
so that they can avoid
important structures

00:55:09.700 --> 00:55:13.158
and go to the right structure
that they intend to operate on.

00:55:18.911 --> 00:55:19.410
OK.

00:55:19.410 --> 00:55:24.390
So you heard Dr. Schiller
talk about electrophysiology

00:55:24.390 --> 00:55:27.880
and recordings from
individual neurons.

00:55:27.880 --> 00:55:32.250
And a lot of what we know
about how the inner ear works

00:55:32.250 --> 00:55:34.316
comes from such
types of experiments.

00:55:35.360 --> 00:55:40.280
And this is an experiment
at the top here

00:55:40.280 --> 00:55:43.915
that gives the responses in
the form of action potentials.

00:55:45.910 --> 00:55:48.750
Each one of these blips is
a little action potential,

00:55:48.750 --> 00:55:54.180
or impulse, or response from
one single auditory nerve

00:55:54.180 --> 00:55:58.860
fiber recorded in the
auditory nerve of a cat, which

00:55:58.860 --> 00:56:02.500
is the very common model
for auditory neuroscience,

00:56:02.500 --> 00:56:05.730
or at least it
was in years past.

00:56:06.750 --> 00:56:13.410
So this response area is a
mapping of sound frequency.

00:56:13.410 --> 00:56:16.160
So this axis is tone frequency.

00:56:16.160 --> 00:56:18.360
And the frequency
of a sound wave form

00:56:18.360 --> 00:56:22.450
is simply how many times
it repeats back and forth

00:56:22.450 --> 00:56:23.085
per second.

00:56:24.690 --> 00:56:27.390
Frequencies that are
common in human hearing

00:56:27.390 --> 00:56:30.810
are, for example, 1,000 hertz.

00:56:30.810 --> 00:56:34.165
This is a graph of kilohertz,
tone frequency in kilohertz.

00:56:35.240 --> 00:56:36.960
And the upper limit
of human hearing

00:56:36.960 --> 00:56:38.895
is approximately 20 kilohertz.

00:56:40.270 --> 00:56:45.590
The lower limit of human hearing
is down around 50 or 100 hertz.

00:56:45.590 --> 00:56:48.580
In terms of smaller
animals like the cat,

00:56:48.580 --> 00:56:53.230
they're shifted up in frequency
of perhaps an octave, maybe

00:56:53.230 --> 00:56:56.800
a doubling of the frequencies
that they're most sensitive to.

00:56:57.880 --> 00:57:00.780
This auditory nerve
fiber responded

00:57:00.780 --> 00:57:04.650
to a variety of frequencies,
except at the very lowest

00:57:04.650 --> 00:57:06.090
sound level.

00:57:06.090 --> 00:57:09.160
The y-axis is a
graph of sound level.

00:57:09.160 --> 00:57:12.910
This is very low
level or soft sound,

00:57:12.910 --> 00:57:14.930
this would be a
medium sound, and this

00:57:14.930 --> 00:57:16.600
would be a very
high level sound.

00:57:17.930 --> 00:57:21.650
At the lowest levels of sound,
the auditory nerve fiber

00:57:21.650 --> 00:57:24.490
only gave a response
to frequencies

00:57:24.490 --> 00:57:29.680
around 10 kilohertz, or
10,000 cycles per second.

00:57:29.680 --> 00:57:34.470
There are some spontaneous
firings from the nerve fiber,

00:57:34.470 --> 00:57:37.630
and those can happen even if
there's no sound presentation.

00:57:37.630 --> 00:57:39.830
These neurons can be
spontaneously active.

00:57:41.830 --> 00:57:44.280
If you outline
this response area,

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:46.950
you can see that it's
very sharply tuned

00:57:46.950 --> 00:57:48.030
to sound frequency.

00:57:48.030 --> 00:57:51.140
It only responds
around 10 kilohertz.

00:57:51.140 --> 00:57:55.190
And this exquisitely sharp
tuning of the auditory nerve

00:57:55.190 --> 00:57:58.550
is the way, perhaps, that the
auditory nerve sends messages

00:57:58.550 --> 00:58:02.480
to the brain that there is only
10 kilohertz that the ears are

00:58:02.480 --> 00:58:06.395
hearing and not 9 kilohertz
and not 11 kilohertz.

00:58:07.480 --> 00:58:08.280
OK?

00:58:08.280 --> 00:58:12.350
If you increase the sound
level to higher levels,

00:58:12.350 --> 00:58:14.510
this auditory nerve
fiber, like others,

00:58:14.510 --> 00:58:17.670
responds to a wide variety
of sound frequencies,

00:58:17.670 --> 00:58:21.530
but it has a very sharp cut
off at the high frequency edge.

00:58:21.530 --> 00:58:24.390
Maybe at 11 kilohertz,
it responds,

00:58:24.390 --> 00:58:27.860
but 11.1 kilohertz
there's no response.

00:58:27.860 --> 00:58:30.450
So the tuning becomes
broader, but there's still

00:58:30.450 --> 00:58:33.870
a really nice, sharp,
high-frequency cut off.

00:58:33.870 --> 00:58:35.660
So what good is this for?

00:58:35.660 --> 00:58:39.610
Well, the ear is very good at
resolving frequency, saying

00:58:39.610 --> 00:58:42.790
there's 10 kilohertz
but not 9 kilohertz.

00:58:42.790 --> 00:58:46.610
And that's very important
for identification of sounds.

00:58:46.610 --> 00:58:50.700
For example, how do we know, if
we're talking on the telephone

00:58:50.700 --> 00:58:54.000
or not seeing the subject
who's talking to us,

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:57.110
that it's a female
speaker or a male speaker

00:58:57.110 --> 00:58:58.980
or an infant speaker?

00:58:58.980 --> 00:59:02.900
Well, male speakers
have lower frequencies

00:59:02.900 --> 00:59:04.510
in their speech sounds.

00:59:04.510 --> 00:59:08.350
And so right away, if we
hear a lot of low frequencies

00:59:08.350 --> 00:59:10.460
in the speech sounds,
we assume we're

00:59:10.460 --> 00:59:12.200
talking to a male speaker.

00:59:12.200 --> 00:59:15.330
And that's, of course, a very
important identification.

00:59:15.330 --> 00:59:19.220
How do we know we're
hearing the vowel A and not

00:59:19.220 --> 00:59:22.930
the vowel E, ah or eh?

00:59:22.930 --> 00:59:25.500
Because of the different
frequencies in the speech

00:59:25.500 --> 00:59:28.540
sounds for those two vowels.

00:59:28.540 --> 00:59:32.320
So frequency coding is
a very important subject

00:59:32.320 --> 00:59:35.640
in the auditory pathway
for identification

00:59:35.640 --> 00:59:38.015
and distinguishing
different types of sounds.

00:59:39.450 --> 00:59:43.650
And one way we know what
frequencies we're listening to

00:59:43.650 --> 00:59:46.190
is if the auditory
nerve fiber's tuned

00:59:46.190 --> 00:59:48.080
to a particular
frequency [INAUDIBLE]

00:59:48.080 --> 00:59:49.760
responding and not the others.

00:59:51.390 --> 00:59:54.240
Now, some very
elegant studies have

00:59:54.240 --> 01:00:00.100
been done to look at
the mapping of frequency

01:00:00.100 --> 01:00:02.105
along the spiral of the cochlea.

01:00:03.200 --> 01:00:05.700
And what those show
is that way down

01:00:05.700 --> 01:00:09.370
at the base of the cochlea,
the very highest frequencies

01:00:09.370 --> 01:00:12.730
are sensed by the hair cells
and the auditory nerve fibers

01:00:12.730 --> 01:00:13.230
there.

01:00:14.530 --> 01:00:17.330
And as you go more
and more apically,

01:00:17.330 --> 01:00:21.630
you arrive at first middle,
and then lower frequencies.

01:00:21.630 --> 01:00:24.390
So there's a very
nice, orderly mapping

01:00:24.390 --> 01:00:29.020
of frequency along the
receptor epithelium,

01:00:29.020 --> 01:00:31.450
or along the cochlea in
the sense of hearing.

01:00:31.450 --> 01:00:35.150
And so, obviously,
the hearing organ

01:00:35.150 --> 01:00:38.170
is set up to distinguish
frequencies and identify

01:00:38.170 --> 01:00:38.670
sounds.

01:00:41.730 --> 01:00:42.670
OK.

01:00:42.670 --> 01:00:48.030
So that's not the only code for
sound frequency that we have.

01:00:48.030 --> 01:00:51.840
We'll talk extensively
about another code

01:00:51.840 --> 01:00:56.190
that uses a time-coding sense.

01:00:56.190 --> 01:01:00.420
And this comes from the way
that auditory nerve fibers

01:01:00.420 --> 01:01:04.070
so-called phase lock to
the sound's waveform.

01:01:05.280 --> 01:01:11.270
Here's a sound stimulus, and
here's auditory firing, first

01:01:11.270 --> 01:01:12.450
with no stimulus.

01:01:12.450 --> 01:01:13.905
It's a fairly random pattern.

01:01:15.310 --> 01:01:18.520
And here is with a
stimulus turned on,

01:01:18.520 --> 01:01:24.070
and you can see that the spikes
line up during a certain phase

01:01:24.070 --> 01:01:27.210
or part of the
stimulus waveform.

01:01:27.210 --> 01:01:29.490
And that's not that
impressive until you

01:01:29.490 --> 01:01:32.660
look at the time scale here.

01:01:32.660 --> 01:01:36.910
As I said before, sounds that
are important in human hearing

01:01:36.910 --> 01:01:40.275
are as high in frequency
as 1 kilohertz.

01:01:41.470 --> 01:01:46.360
So if this is going back and
forth 1,000 times per second,

01:01:46.360 --> 01:01:50.200
then the scale bar here for one
period would be 1 millisecond.

01:01:51.420 --> 01:01:55.400
And so the auditory nerve is
keeping track and firing only

01:01:55.400 --> 01:02:00.070
on a certain or preferential
phase of the stimulus waveform

01:02:00.070 --> 01:02:02.940
with the capability
of milliseconds.

01:02:02.940 --> 01:02:03.440
OK?

01:02:03.440 --> 01:02:08.350
And this is a much better
phase-locking pattern

01:02:08.350 --> 01:02:09.790
than you get in other senses.

01:02:09.790 --> 01:02:12.160
For example, in
the visual system,

01:02:12.160 --> 01:02:17.680
when you flash the light on
and off just even 100 flashes

01:02:17.680 --> 01:02:21.590
per second, everything
sort of blears out,

01:02:21.590 --> 01:02:24.360
and you sort of don't
have any phase locking

01:02:24.360 --> 01:02:27.560
the way you do in the
auditory nerves firing.

01:02:27.560 --> 01:02:32.290
So this is a very nice coding
for sound frequency that

01:02:32.290 --> 01:02:34.960
is sort of a
secondary way to code.

01:02:34.960 --> 01:02:40.050
This is a very important
coding for musical sounds.

01:02:40.050 --> 01:02:44.400
Musical sounds, for
example, like an octave,

01:02:44.400 --> 01:02:49.570
1 kilohertz and 2 kilohertz,
a doubling of sound frequency,

01:02:49.570 --> 01:02:53.960
have very similar patterns
in their temporal responses

01:02:53.960 --> 01:02:56.320
to those two frequencies
that probably

01:02:56.320 --> 01:03:01.290
makes an octave a very beautiful
musical interval to listen to.

01:03:01.290 --> 01:03:05.860
And it appears in music of many
different types of cultures.

01:03:05.860 --> 01:03:07.600
So one of the
demonstrations that I'll

01:03:07.600 --> 01:03:12.170
play for you is
an A for 40 hertz

01:03:12.170 --> 01:03:15.990
and an octave above that,
880 hertz, and you'll

01:03:15.990 --> 01:03:19.310
hear how beautiful the
two sound together.

01:03:19.310 --> 01:03:21.900
And then I'll mistune
them, which is easy for me

01:03:21.900 --> 01:03:24.670
to do because I'm an
amateur violinist,

01:03:24.670 --> 01:03:26.410
and I'll be doing
this on a violin.

01:03:26.410 --> 01:03:30.680
And it's pretty easy to
have a mistuned octave,

01:03:30.680 --> 01:03:33.550
and it sounds so awful
and very dissonant

01:03:33.550 --> 01:03:35.160
when you listen to it.

01:03:35.160 --> 01:03:37.730
And one of the reasons for
that, the reason for that,

01:03:37.730 --> 01:03:41.090
is the difference
in phase locking

01:03:41.090 --> 01:03:45.382
for the two dissonant sounds
versus the two consonant

01:03:45.382 --> 01:03:45.881
sounds.

01:03:50.341 --> 01:03:50.840
OK.

01:03:50.840 --> 01:03:53.960
So we will talk
about what happens

01:03:53.960 --> 01:03:56.395
when you have problems
with your hearing.

01:03:58.410 --> 01:04:01.100
One of the main
problems with hearing

01:04:01.100 --> 01:04:04.340
that causes loss,
complete loss of hearing,

01:04:04.340 --> 01:04:10.200
is when the receptor
cells are attacked

01:04:10.200 --> 01:04:15.770
by various types of
insults, diseases, drugs,

01:04:15.770 --> 01:04:20.120
the aging process,
stimulation, or listening

01:04:20.120 --> 01:04:22.370
to very high-level sounds.

01:04:22.370 --> 01:04:24.270
These can all kill
the hair cells.

01:04:25.550 --> 01:04:28.890
And in the mammalian cochlea,
once the hair cells are lost

01:04:28.890 --> 01:04:30.700
they never grow back.

01:04:30.700 --> 01:04:33.070
And there's very active
interest in trying

01:04:33.070 --> 01:04:35.720
to get hair cells to
regenerate by using

01:04:35.720 --> 01:04:38.910
stem cells or various
growth factors,

01:04:38.910 --> 01:04:40.485
but so far that
can't be achieved.

01:04:42.040 --> 01:04:45.160
Luckily, in the
auditory periphery,

01:04:45.160 --> 01:04:47.860
even if you lose the
hair cells, which

01:04:47.860 --> 01:04:50.700
is the major cause
of deafness, you

01:04:50.700 --> 01:04:53.310
retain your auditory
nerve fibers.

01:04:53.310 --> 01:04:57.050
So these blue structures here
are the auditory nerve fibers

01:04:57.050 --> 01:04:59.070
coming from the hair cells.

01:04:59.070 --> 01:05:02.480
And even if the hair
cells are killed

01:05:02.480 --> 01:05:05.330
by these various insults,
the auditory nerve fibers,

01:05:05.330 --> 01:05:06.745
or at least many
of them, remain.

01:05:08.920 --> 01:05:12.550
So you heard Dr. Schiller talk
about electrical stimulation.

01:05:13.700 --> 01:05:16.880
You can put an electrical
stimulating electrode

01:05:16.880 --> 01:05:21.590
in the inner ear and stimulate
those remaining auditory nerve

01:05:21.590 --> 01:05:25.510
fibers to fire impulses
that are sent to the brain.

01:05:25.510 --> 01:05:27.490
And if you hook that
system up right,

01:05:27.490 --> 01:05:30.065
you have a so-called
cochlear implant.

01:05:30.065 --> 01:05:35.530
The cochlear implant has a
microphone that detects sound.

01:05:35.530 --> 01:05:41.760
It has a processor that converts
that sound into various pulses

01:05:41.760 --> 01:05:43.990
of electrical stimulating
current, which

01:05:43.990 --> 01:05:46.700
can be applied to a
system of electrodes

01:05:46.700 --> 01:05:49.360
that is inserted
into the cochlea.

01:05:49.360 --> 01:05:53.710
The cochlea is a
beautiful bony capsule.

01:05:53.710 --> 01:05:55.990
You can snake this electrode in.

01:05:55.990 --> 01:05:57.100
It doesn't move away.

01:05:57.100 --> 01:05:58.360
You can glue it in place.

01:05:59.540 --> 01:06:02.830
You can lead the electrode
out to the processor that

01:06:02.830 --> 01:06:08.160
activates it when the
subject hears a sound that's

01:06:08.160 --> 01:06:09.830
detected by the microphone.

01:06:09.830 --> 01:06:14.520
And this cochlear implant
is the most successful

01:06:14.520 --> 01:06:17.460
neural prosthesis
that's been developed.

01:06:17.460 --> 01:06:21.700
It's implanted all the time
at Mass Eye and Ear Infirmary.

01:06:21.700 --> 01:06:24.950
It's paid for by insurance.

01:06:24.950 --> 01:06:27.680
These days, insurance pays
for a cochlear implant

01:06:27.680 --> 01:06:29.545
in your left cochlea
if you're deaf,

01:06:29.545 --> 01:06:32.230
and it will also pay for
another cochlear implant

01:06:32.230 --> 01:06:35.310
in your right cochlea
if you're deaf.

01:06:35.310 --> 01:06:38.790
So the metric for how
successful this is,

01:06:38.790 --> 01:06:41.940
is whether the subject who's
using the cochlear implant

01:06:41.940 --> 01:06:43.090
can understand speech.

01:06:44.150 --> 01:06:47.750
And so you can have
various tests of speech.

01:06:47.750 --> 01:06:51.510
A speaker can give a sentence,
and the person can respond.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:55.780
The speaker can give
various simple words,

01:06:55.780 --> 01:06:57.710
and the cochlear implant
user can respond.

01:06:57.710 --> 01:07:02.021
You can test these individuals
in a very straightforward

01:07:02.021 --> 01:07:02.520
manner.

01:07:02.520 --> 01:07:07.310
And we will have a demonstration
by a cochlear implant user.

01:07:07.310 --> 01:07:11.720
I have an undergraduate
demonstrator who's here at MIT.

01:07:11.720 --> 01:07:15.300
And she'll come in and
she'll describe and show you

01:07:15.300 --> 01:07:18.790
her cochlear implant, and
you can ask her questions.

01:07:18.790 --> 01:07:23.150
And there, I guarantee you with
this particular demonstration

01:07:23.150 --> 01:07:25.720
that I have in mind,
that she won't always

01:07:25.720 --> 01:07:27.870
understand your questions.

01:07:27.870 --> 01:07:31.780
I have had really great
cochlear implant users

01:07:31.780 --> 01:07:34.810
who are superstars, that
understand every word.

01:07:34.810 --> 01:07:38.470
But the more norm is they
understand much of what you say

01:07:38.470 --> 01:07:40.150
but not everything.

01:07:40.150 --> 01:07:42.840
And this particular room is
a little bit challenging.

01:07:42.840 --> 01:07:44.545
There's some noise
in the background.

01:07:45.750 --> 01:07:49.100
It's not one-on-one,
so the implant user

01:07:49.100 --> 01:07:52.080
won't know exactly
who's speaking at once.

01:07:52.080 --> 01:07:56.780
And in this case, the person
just has one ear implanted,

01:07:56.780 --> 01:08:01.840
so her ability to localize
sounds is compromised.

01:08:01.840 --> 01:08:04.980
And she won't know who's asking
the question until she sort

01:08:04.980 --> 01:08:07.200
of zeroes in a little bit on it.

01:08:07.200 --> 01:08:11.700
So you'll see the cochlear
implant is not perfect,

01:08:11.700 --> 01:08:15.200
but it's pretty
good in its metric

01:08:15.200 --> 01:08:16.899
for speech comprehension.

01:08:22.230 --> 01:08:22.730
OK.

01:08:23.800 --> 01:08:27.340
Now, I said this particular
cochlear implant user only

01:08:27.340 --> 01:08:29.149
has one implant in one ear.

01:08:30.565 --> 01:08:34.590
To really be good
at localizing sound,

01:08:34.590 --> 01:08:37.770
we need to have
two ears, and there

01:08:37.770 --> 01:08:40.809
are the so-called binaural
cues for sound localization.

01:08:42.380 --> 01:08:46.779
Here's a subject listening
to a sound source.

01:08:46.779 --> 01:08:49.420
The sound source is
emitting sound here,

01:08:49.420 --> 01:08:52.454
and it gets to the
subject's left ear first.

01:08:53.700 --> 01:08:56.950
And a short time later, it gets
to the subject's right ear.

01:08:56.950 --> 01:09:01.580
And that's one of the cues for
binaural localization of sound,

01:09:01.580 --> 01:09:03.800
which is interaural
time difference.

01:09:04.830 --> 01:09:10.814
The velocity of sound in air
is 342 meters per second.

01:09:12.279 --> 01:09:14.490
And depending on how
big your head is,

01:09:14.490 --> 01:09:18.080
you can calculate the
Interaural Time Difference.

01:09:18.080 --> 01:09:20.890
And of course,
that ITD is maximal

01:09:20.890 --> 01:09:25.529
if the sound source is
located off to one side,

01:09:25.529 --> 01:09:27.791
and it's exactly zero
if the sound source

01:09:27.791 --> 01:09:29.390
is located straight ahead.

01:09:30.290 --> 01:09:30.790
OK?

01:09:30.790 --> 01:09:34.340
So that is a cue for
localization of sounds.

01:09:34.340 --> 01:09:38.051
We'll listen to sounds that
differ in interaural time

01:09:38.051 --> 01:09:38.550
difference.

01:09:38.550 --> 01:09:41.080
We can play these through
headphones for you.

01:09:41.080 --> 01:09:42.990
And we'll have some
demonstrations of that.

01:09:44.290 --> 01:09:47.189
The other binaural cue
for sound localization

01:09:47.189 --> 01:09:50.500
is the interaural
level difference.

01:09:50.500 --> 01:09:53.075
Here is the same sound
source, same subject.

01:09:54.380 --> 01:09:59.370
This ear will experience a
slightly higher sound level

01:09:59.370 --> 01:10:02.840
than the other ear because
sound can't perfectly

01:10:02.840 --> 01:10:04.305
bend around the head.

01:10:04.305 --> 01:10:06.670
The head creates a sound shadow.

01:10:06.670 --> 01:10:10.670
And this is especially important
for high frequencies of sound,

01:10:10.670 --> 01:10:13.130
like above 3 kilohertz.

01:10:13.130 --> 01:10:17.340
So that is a second binaural
cue for sound localization.

01:10:18.470 --> 01:10:21.160
We'll listen to those cues.

01:10:21.160 --> 01:10:26.120
And we'll talk a lot about
the brainstem processing

01:10:26.120 --> 01:10:28.593
of those binaural cues
for sound localization.

01:10:29.610 --> 01:10:33.930
If you compare the visual
and the auditory pathways--

01:10:33.930 --> 01:10:36.470
this is a block diagram
of the auditory pathway,

01:10:36.470 --> 01:10:39.440
and there are a lot
of brainstem nuclei.

01:10:40.670 --> 01:10:45.900
We have the cochlear nucleus,
the superior olivary complex,

01:10:45.900 --> 01:10:48.065
and the inferior colliculus.

01:10:48.065 --> 01:10:53.030
And these latter two get input
from the two ears on the two

01:10:53.030 --> 01:10:56.190
sides, and they
probably do the bulk

01:10:56.190 --> 01:10:59.406
of the neural processing
for sound localization.

01:11:00.750 --> 01:11:04.020
You don't have to do that
so much in the visual system

01:11:04.020 --> 01:11:05.910
because the visual
system, in a sense,

01:11:05.910 --> 01:11:09.515
has a mapping of external
space already on the retina.

01:11:10.540 --> 01:11:13.920
But remember, the inner
ears map sound frequency.

01:11:13.920 --> 01:11:16.850
And so the inner ears
themselves don't know

01:11:16.850 --> 01:11:19.730
or don't have a
good cue for where

01:11:19.730 --> 01:11:22.220
the sound is localized in space.

01:11:22.220 --> 01:11:25.750
Instead, you need input
from the two sides,

01:11:25.750 --> 01:11:28.610
and you need a lot
of neural processing

01:11:28.610 --> 01:11:31.640
to help you determine
where that sound source is

01:11:31.640 --> 01:11:33.200
coming from in space.

01:11:34.880 --> 01:11:35.380
OK.

01:11:35.380 --> 01:11:37.440
So we'll talk about
the neural processing

01:11:37.440 --> 01:11:38.815
of those binaural cues.

01:11:41.060 --> 01:11:42.920
We'll talk toward
the end of the course

01:11:42.920 --> 01:11:46.940
about the various
auditory cortical fields.

01:11:46.940 --> 01:11:50.780
These are the cortical fields
in the side of the cat's brain.

01:11:52.070 --> 01:11:54.090
So this is the
front of the brain.

01:11:54.090 --> 01:11:56.220
This is looking at the
left side of the brain.

01:11:56.220 --> 01:11:59.360
This is the rear of the brain
where the occipital lobes are,

01:11:59.360 --> 01:12:01.650
where V1 is.

01:12:01.650 --> 01:12:03.650
And on the side or
temporal cortex,

01:12:03.650 --> 01:12:06.340
you have the auditory
fields, including

01:12:06.340 --> 01:12:09.000
A1 or primary auditory cortex.

01:12:11.130 --> 01:12:13.720
And we'll talk, at least
touch upon a little bit,

01:12:13.720 --> 01:12:18.190
toward the end of the course
the human auditory-- primary

01:12:18.190 --> 01:12:21.820
auditory cortical field is right
here on the superior surface

01:12:21.820 --> 01:12:25.850
of the superior temporal gyrus.

01:12:25.850 --> 01:12:29.930
And just near it, it could be
called an auditory association

01:12:29.930 --> 01:12:33.090
area, is an area
called Wernicke's area

01:12:33.090 --> 01:12:35.925
that's very important in
processing of language.

01:12:36.970 --> 01:12:38.480
And of course,
connected with that

01:12:38.480 --> 01:12:41.790
is the Broca's area, which
is another important language

01:12:41.790 --> 01:12:46.270
center, in the dominant
hemisphere at least, of humans.

01:12:46.270 --> 01:12:49.880
So we'll touch upon that at
the very end of the course.

01:12:49.880 --> 01:12:54.240
And we'll also have a special
topic called bat echolocation,

01:12:54.240 --> 01:12:59.320
how bats use their auditory
sense to navigate around

01:12:59.320 --> 01:13:01.670
the world at night even
without their vision.

01:13:03.870 --> 01:13:07.730
And finally, at the very last
class period before the review

01:13:07.730 --> 01:13:11.950
sessions, we'll all go over
for a tour of the research lab

01:13:11.950 --> 01:13:14.650
where I work at the
Massachusetts Eye and Ear

01:13:14.650 --> 01:13:15.810
Infirmary.

01:13:15.810 --> 01:13:19.150
So it's across the Longfellow
Bridge right at the end

01:13:19.150 --> 01:13:21.530
there where the arrow is.

01:13:21.530 --> 01:13:24.570
And we'll have some
demonstrations there.

01:13:24.570 --> 01:13:27.210
I think last year we
had a demonstration

01:13:27.210 --> 01:13:31.640
on single-unit recording
from an awake animal that's

01:13:31.640 --> 01:13:32.735
listening to sound.

01:13:33.860 --> 01:13:38.140
We had measurements from humans
of the so-called otoacoustic

01:13:38.140 --> 01:13:38.860
emissions.

01:13:38.860 --> 01:13:41.540
These are sounds
that can be detected

01:13:41.540 --> 01:13:44.630
in the ear canal with a
very sensitive microphone.

01:13:44.630 --> 01:13:47.100
They're used in
tests of hearing.

01:13:47.100 --> 01:13:49.890
And I also think
we had a discussion

01:13:49.890 --> 01:13:52.560
of imaging of the
auditory system.

01:13:52.560 --> 01:13:56.720
And of course, if you've ever
listened to an MRI machine,

01:13:56.720 --> 01:13:58.620
it's sort of described
sometimes as being

01:13:58.620 --> 01:14:01.850
as loud as being inside
a washing machine.

01:14:01.850 --> 01:14:04.670
And it's very
challenging for people

01:14:04.670 --> 01:14:07.650
that image subjects
who are listening

01:14:07.650 --> 01:14:10.270
to especially very
low-level sounds

01:14:10.270 --> 01:14:14.270
when there's all this background
noise coming from the imaging

01:14:14.270 --> 01:14:14.770
machine.

01:14:14.770 --> 01:14:16.640
So there's some
special things that

01:14:16.640 --> 01:14:19.390
are done to minimize
the noise coming

01:14:19.390 --> 01:14:23.550
from the imager in
auditory studies.

